ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach to 3Sum is conceptually straightforward but computationally expensive. The intuition is that if we examine every possible combination of three elements in the array, we're guaranteed to find all triplets that sum to zero. This works because we're performing an exhaustive search through the entire solution space. The algorithm proceeds as follows: First, we initialize an empty set to store unique triplets. Then we use three nested loops: the outermost loop selects the first element (i from 0 to n-3), the middle loop selects the second element (j from i+1 to n-2), and the innermost loop selects the third element (k from j+1 to n-1). For each combination (nums[i], nums[j], nums[k]), we check if their sum equals zero. If it does, we create a sorted tuple of the three values and add it to our set. Sorting the triplet before storing ensures that different orderings of the same three numbers are treated as identical, effectively removing duplicates. After examining all combinations, we convert the set to a list and return it. The time complexity is O(n³) because we have three nested loops each iterating up to n times. The space complexity is O(k) where k is the number of unique triplets found, but in the worst case when all triplets sum to zero, this could approach O(n³) due to the set storage. This approach connects directly to the key subroutine (L1) which is the triple nested loop structure. Common mistakes include: forgetting to sort triplets before adding to the set (leading to duplicate triplets), using indices incorrectly in loop ranges (potentially missing combinations or causing index errors), and not handling empty or small arrays properly. The real code pattern involves careful loop boundary management and proper tuple creation.

Pseudocode:
function threeSum(nums):
    n = length(nums)
    result_set = empty set
    for i from 0 to n-3:
        for j from i+1 to n-2:
            for k from j+1 to n-1:
                if nums[i] + nums[j] + nums[k] == 0:
                    triplet = sorted([nums[i], nums[j], nums[k]])
                    add triplet to result_set
    return list(result_set)

The triple nested loop structure is the computational engine of the brute force 3Sum solution. The intuition is that by systematically varying three indices through all possible combinations, we can examine every triplet in the array exactly once. This works because we're essentially performing a combinatorial enumeration: for an array of size n, there are C(n,3) = n(n-1)(n-2)/6 possible triplets, and our nested loops visit each one. The algorithm uses careful index management: the outermost loop (i) runs from 0 to n-3, the middle loop (j) runs from i+1 to n-2, and the innermost loop (k) runs from j+1 to n-1. This ensures that i < j < k always, preventing duplicate examination of the same combination in different orders. The step-by-step process is: initialize i=0, then for each i, initialize j=i+1, then for each j, initialize k=j+1, then for each k, we have a unique combination (i,j,k). After processing all k values, increment j, and after all j values, increment i. The time complexity is O(n³) because each loop can run up to n times. The space complexity is O(1) for just the loop structure itself (not counting storage for results). This connects to the core logic (L2) which is checking if the sum of elements at these indices equals zero. Common mistakes include: using incorrect loop boundaries (like i≤n instead of i≤n-3), not maintaining the i<j<k relationship (leading to duplicate combinations), and off-by-one errors. The real code pattern involves three for-loops with carefully calculated ranges.

Pseudocode:
function generateTriplets(nums):
    n = length(nums)
    triplets = empty list
    for i from 0 to n-3:
        for j from i+1 to n-2:
            for k from j+1 to n-1:
                triplets.append((i, j, k))
    return triplets

This building block addresses how to prepare a valid triplet for storage in a set to ensure uniqueness. The intuition is that by sorting three numbers, we create a canonical representation: regardless of the original order in the array, the same three numbers will always produce the same sorted list. This works because sorting is deterministic - for any three numbers a, b, c, after sorting we'll always get them in ascending order. We then convert to a tuple because sets in Python (and similar data structures in other languages) require hashable elements, and lists are not hashable while tuples are. The algorithm is straightforward: given three numbers, create a list containing them, sort the list using any sorting algorithm (for just 3 elements, even bubble sort is efficient), then convert the sorted list to a tuple. For three elements, we can optimize by manually comparing and arranging them, but using built-in sort is simpler. The step-by-step process: 1) Create list = [a, b, c], 2) Sort the list in ascending order (could use list.sort() or sorted()), 3) Convert to tuple using tuple(list). The time complexity is O(1) since we're sorting only 3 elements (constant time). The space complexity is O(1) for the temporary list and tuple. This connects to the basic operation (L4) of comparing two numbers. Common mistakes include: forgetting to sort (leading to duplicate representations), trying to add lists directly to sets (causing type errors), and incorrect sorting order. The real code pattern involves the sorted() function and tuple() constructor.

Pseudocode:
function prepareTriplet(a, b, c):
    lst = [a, b, c]
    sorted_lst = sorted(lst)  # returns new sorted list
    return tuple(sorted_lst)

This basic operation is fundamental to sorting: comparing two numbers to determine which is smaller, larger, or if they're equal. The intuition is that sorting algorithms rely on repeatedly comparing pairs of elements to arrange them in order. This works because we can define a total order for numbers (specifically integers in this context): for any two numbers a and b, exactly one of the following is true: a < b, a > b, or a = b. The algorithm is simple: given two numbers, use comparison operators (<, >, ==) to determine their relationship. In the context of sorting a 3-element list, we might need to perform several comparisons: first compare the first two elements, then compare the result with the third element, etc. The step-by-step process for a single comparison: 1) Evaluate a < b, which returns True if a is less than b, False otherwise, 2) Evaluate a > b, which returns True if a is greater than b, False otherwise, 3) Evaluate a == b, which returns True if they're equal. These comparisons form the basis of any sorting algorithm. The time complexity is O(1) for a single comparison. The space complexity is O(1). This connects to the concept foundation (L5) of understanding numbers and their properties. Common mistakes include: confusing comparison operators (using = instead of == for equality), not handling edge cases like negative numbers correctly, and integer overflow in some languages (though not typically in Python). The real code pattern involves simple if-else statements or comparison expressions.

Pseudocode:
function compare(a, b):
    if a < b:
        return "a is less than b"
    elif a > b:
        return "a is greater than b"
    else:
        return "a equals b"
